(634, '<![CDATA[<div class=\"col-sm-192 col-lg-192 col-md-192 col-xs-192 archive_banner\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-responsive zoom-img\" src=\"http://images.scdaarchitects.com/www_scdaarchitects_com/SCDA_Soo_Chan_Lincoln_Modern_Singapore_13.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"628\" height=\"668\" data-enlarge=\"http://images.scdaarchitects.com/www_scdaarchitects_com/SCDA_Soo_Chan_Lincoln_Modern_Singapore_10.jpg\" data-height=\"1080\" data-width=\"1015\" /></div>\n<div class=\"archive_intro\">\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><strong>LINCOLN MODERN</strong>  |  Singapore</p>\n<p>Lincoln Modern is a 30-storey condominium in the form of 56 split-level apartments, studios and penthouses. These residential apartments are a development of principles first explored in Le Corbusier&#8217;s two-storey prototype dwelling for the 1922 Immeubles-Villas project, which was subsequently displayed in the Esprit Nouveau Pavilion at the 1925 Paris Exposition. The exposition showed drawings of the dwelling in its possible contexts, both as a stacked unit and as a detached suburban villa.</p>\n</div>\n<div class=\"col-sm-192 col-lg-192 col-md-192 col-xs-192 archive_banner\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-responsive zoom-img\" src=\"http://images.scdaarchitects.com/www_scdaarchitects_com/SCDA_Soo_Chan_Lincoln_Modern_Singapore_33.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"628\" height=\"816\" data-enlarge=\"http://images.scdaarchitects.com/www_scdaarchitects_com/SCDA_Soo_Chan_Lincoln_Modern_Singapore_30.jpg\" data-height=\"1080\" data-width=\"832\" /></div>\n<div class=\"col-sm-192 col-lg-192 col-md-192 col-xs-192 archive_banner\"><img loading=\"lazy\" class=\"img-responsive zoom-img\" src=\"http://images.scdaarchitects.com/www_scdaarchitects_com/SCDA_Soo_Chan_Lincoln_Modern_Singapore_71.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"630\" height=\"330\" data-enlarge=\"http://images.scdaarchitects.com/www_scdaarchitects_com/SCDA_Soo_Chan_Lincoln_Modern_Singapore_70.jpg\" data-height=\"1080\" data-width=\"1284\" /></div>\n<div class=\"col-sm-192 